'''Avenimiento''' (literally, "agreement" or "compromise")<ref>{{cite web|title=Collins Spanish-English Dictionary English Translation of "avenimiento"|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/spanish-english/avenimiento|publisher=Collins|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref> was a legal concept in the [[Argentine Penal Code]], which stated that if a rape victim over the age of 16 agreed to marry her rapist, he could be freed from prison.<ref name="AI">{{cite news|last=Flint|first=Hannah|title=Congress Pass Important Bills in First Session of the Year|url=http://www.argentinaindependent.com/currentaffairs/newsfromargentina/congress-pass-important-bills-in-first-session-of-the-year/|accessdate=23 September 2012|newspaper=The Argentina Independent|date=15 March 2012|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130117080815/http://www.argentinaindependent.com/currentaffairs/newsfromargentina/congress-pass-important-bills-in-first-session-of-the-year/|archivedate=2013-01-17|dead-url=no|df=}}</ref>
The concept of avenimiento was created as part of a 1998 overhaul of Argentinian laws related to [[sexual offences]]. Before 1998, this section of the law was called "Offences to Honesty": afterwards it was renamed "Offences to Sexual Integrity."<ref>{{cite journal|last=Pimentel|first=Silvia |author2=Valéria Pandjiarjian |author3=Juliana Belloque|title="Legitimate Defense of Honor" Illegitimate Impunity of Murders|journal=UNICAMP Center for Gender Studies|year=2006|pages=138|url=http://www.bibliotecadigital.unicamp.br/document/?down=50807|accessdate=23 September 2012}}</ref>
The concept has been widely criticized by [[international human rights]] organizations, and was removed from the penal code in March 2012, following a unanimous vote of 51 Argentinian senators.<ref name="AI"/>
