The '''Unlicensed National Information Infrastructure''' ('''U-NII''')<ref>[http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/61748 "15.07.2005, Heise: 5 GHz WLAN to be available all over Europe" www.heise.de] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050807080924/http://www.heise.de/english/newsticker/news/61748 |date=2005-08-07 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cisco.com/univercd/cc/td/doc/product/wireless/cb21ag/icg02/winglskh.htm|title="Cisco: Glossary" www.cisco.com|publisher=}}</ref> [[radio band]] is part of the [[radio frequency spectrum]] used by [[802.11a|IEEE-802.11a]] devices and by many wireless ISPs. It operates over four ranges:

*U-NII Low (U-NII-1<ref name=cisco1>{{cite web|url=http://www.cisco.com/en/US/prod/collateral/wireless/ps5679/ps5861/prod_white_paper0900aecd801c4a88_ps5279_Products_White_Paper.html|title="Dynamic Frequency Selection for 5 GHz WLAN in the US and Canada" www.cisco.com|publisher=}}</ref>): 5.150-5.250&nbsp;GHz. Originally limited to indoor use only.  Regulations required use of an integrated antenna, with power limited to 50&nbsp;mW.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|url=http://www.hallikainen.com/FccRules/2014/15/407/|title=FCC 15.407 as of October 1, 2014 - hallikainen.com|website=www.hallikainen.com}}</ref>  Rules changed in 2014 to permit outdoor operation, maximum fixed power 1 watt, maximum fixed EIRP 4 watts (+36 dBm) point-to-multipoint, 200 watts (+53 dBm) point-to-point. [http://www.fcc.gov/document/5-ghz-u-nii-ro]  However, strict out-of-band emission rules limit practical point-to-point power to lower levels.
*U-NII Mid (U-NII-2A<ref name=cisco1 />): 5.250-5.350&nbsp;GHz. Both outdoor and indoor use, subject to [[Dynamic Frequency Selection]] (DFS, or radar avoidance).  Regulations allow for a user-installable antenna.<ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|url=http://www.atcb.com/publicdocs/fcc-03-287a1-UNII-Changes.pdf|title=FCC-03-287A1.doc<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> Power limited to 250&nbsp;mW<ref name=autogenerated1 />
*U-NII-2B: 5.350-5.470&nbsp;GHz. Currently 120MHz of spectrum <u>not allocated</u> by the FCC for unlicensed use.
*U-NII Worldwide (U-NII-2C / U-NII-2e): 5.470-5.725&nbsp;GHz. Both outdoor and indoor use, subject to [[Dynamic Frequency Selection]] (DFS, or radar avoidance).<ref name=autogenerated2 /> Power limited to 250&nbsp;mW.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> This spectrum was added by the FCC in 2003 to "align the frequency bands used by U-NII devices in the United States with bands in other parts of the world".<ref name=autogenerated2 /> The FCC currently has an interim limitation on operations on channels which overlap the 5600 - 5650&nbsp;MHz band.<ref name=fcc1>{{cite web|url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/oetcf/kdb/forms/FTSSearchResultPage.cfm?id=41732&switch=P|title="15E, Dynamic Frequency Selection, DFS, DFS Approval" fcc.gov|publisher=}}</ref>
*U-NII Upper (U-NII-3<ref name=fcc-new-unii>{{cite web|url=https://transition.fcc.gov/bureaus/oet/ea/presentations/files/apr14/51-5GHz-First-R&O-TCB-April-09,-2014-_4-AW.pdf|title="What's New With Unlicensed National Information Infrastructure (U-NII)"|publisher=}}</ref>): 5.725 to 5.850&nbsp;GHz. Sometimes referred to as ''U-NII / ISM'' due to overlap with the [[ISM band]]. Regulations allow for a user-installable antenna. Power limited to 1W<ref name=autogenerated1 />
*DSRC/ITS (U-NII-4<ref name=fcc-unii4>{{cite web|url=https://www.fcc.gov/news-events/blog/2015/02/23/driving-wi-fi-ahead-upper-5-ghz-band|title=Driving Wi-Fi Ahead: the Upper 5 GHz Band|date=23 February 2015|publisher=}}</ref>): 5.850 to 5.925&nbsp;GHz. At present U-NII-4 spectrum is being considered by the FCC for unlicensed use. U-NII-4 is presently only usable for [[Dedicated_short-range_communications|Dedicated Short Range Communications Service (DSRC)]] and licensed Amateur Radio Operators.
